segments.text: With Frank W.R. Hubert, he was more of a person who worked behind the scenes.
I'm really not sure if I ever heard him give a speech, but everyone seemed to know him.
And he was, if you want to call it glad-handing, you know, he was right there and everybody was coming to him and he was going to various people.
And with every one of these people, he was always introducing me.
He was saying, this is Dr. Glenn Johnson.
He's one of our new faculty members from Columbia University.
And we like what he's doing, et cetera, et cetera.
And they would then start asking me questions.
And they were just as inquisitive as the faculty had been when I first came down there on that interview.
about this non-graded school and the lander's interaction analysis and what Jerry and I were doing with this block program.
They were all interested in that.
Now that block program, Jerry and I had nothing to do with the formulation of that.
That was strictly Paul Hensarling, Bill Graves, and his counterpart at the secondary level.
They had laid all the groundwork for that the previous year.
And as I recall, the second or third year, that was operational.
They started to get some...

nice recognition even at the national level for that that program that block program so they get all the accolades for that and i may have mentioned this already but one of the other blessings was having earl rutter with real public education experience out in the schools and frank hubert the same
and both of them having a lot of experience in the real world of Austin bureaucracy and politics.
That's right.
Rudder in the Land Office and Hubert in the Department of Education, and they both knew their way around the legislature and other.
Did you all have any interaction in those early years with the Coordinating Board?
Yes.
Anytime we had a change in our degree program, we had to go over and make presentations.
They were brief, but there were more inquiries, you know, why this, why that, and getting clarification.
You mentioned something just a second ago.
Can we back that up?
I want to hear it.
Yes, hearing that replay, it finally registered with me while you were talking.
Another thing that surprised me and tuned me in to just how politically oriented or connected Earl Rudder and Frank W.R. Hubert were, I remember sitting in his office one day

And he picks up the phone and carries on a conversation with Congressman Tiger Teague in Washington, DC, which really impressed me that somebody could do that, pick up the phone and talk to a congressman with the power that
Tiger Teague had because he was a very powerful congressman and a real spokesperson for Veteran Affairs and so forth.
That was very impressive.
And I said we made presentations to the Coordinating Board.
make presentations to the coordinating board.
Our presentations were with J.W.
Edgar's group, but the coordinating board, it seems to me we were in the background and there to answer questions, but it was always the vice president
or later the provost who really went to the coordinating board and made presentations.
I don't think we ever made, I don't recall now in retrospect ever making a presentation to the coordinating board.
Did you or your colleagues work with

commissioner jack kenny williams who headed the coordinating board at that time did y'all work with him no he had left by the time i came in 67 but i'm sure somebody like maybe don barker or somebody like that may have been here long enough to right in those earliest years what were your personal goals
You must have set some goals for yourself.
Yes, I really wanted to become the best I could become and move up the academic rank to associate and full professor, establish some research efforts, and to write.
I enjoyed writing.
I had already written.
In fact, when you brought that up, when I came down for the interview, the faculty were
were very impressed that I already had publications in national refereed journals.
I wasn't even in the college or university setting, and yet I'd already published in pretty prestigious academic journals.
And I always enjoyed writing.
Even my first year of teaching, I was writing articles that would appear in the newspapers.
And I was setting up activities where my students would become involved.
And newspaper photographers would come in and photograph.
And we'd have a little caption story to go with it.
And I continued that kind of writing
when I was working on my master's degree, my doctorate.
that type of writing plus writing for academic journals.
And when I became principal down at Clayton, Missouri, they asked me to assume responsibility for the Clayton School News.
So I assumed that responsibility and would have usually an article in each monthly news that came out.
I'd write something specifically.
So I always enjoyed the writing.
In your first years here, did you have a favorite research topic?
I didn't have time to really write that first year.
I think the newness, the five-course load, the pulling together of this new block program that Paul and Bill Graves wanted us to.
to establish just devoured almost all of my time.
So I don't think I had time to really do research or write that first year.
Of course, we were putting together proposals, too, new courses.
We were trying to get new courses generated.
That was time consuming.
Now there must have been some good stories that you can recall about you as a non-Texan beginning to have Aggie students in your classes.
There must have been some learning experiences you can share.
Actually, I was pretty much impressed with the Aggie students.
That first year, I doubt if I had more than two or three young men in the courses.
They were all ladies.
And they just seemed like very clean cut kids.
A lot of times, people would be out maybe a year.

and want to become a teacher and they'd have to come in and take our courses and they seemed mature so I really didn't have any great unusual stories I just liked these people I thought they were really
really good people and interested in doing what they could to improve education.
Did you have any encounters with Aggie traditions in those first years?
Oh yes, and very impressive.
I mean starting with, and I took in all of them that first year.
They would talk about silver taps.
I wanted to see silver taps, so I saw silver taps.
Muster, I wanted to see what this was.
I was very impressed.
Bonfire, that first ball before the University of Texas game, a game in which we won and surprised everyone.
It was the year where Gene Stallings won the Southwest Conference, and we'd lost the first four games.
So nobody was expecting this to happen, but...
All the tradition and so forth was extremely impressive.
The Corps of Cadets was impressive.
The march-ins to the football games, I had to go over and see that.
Those were all impressive to me.
Do you remember any instances of Aggie good bull or pranks

in or around any of your classes didn't run into that in any of my classes but the very first yell practice i went with bowled me over because all these good kids and nice kids and so forth suddenly took on a whole different complexion that midnight yell practice and
They were using the language that even turned my face red.
And I kind of had a few comments with my colleagues after that.
When I'd been to my first Yale practice, I didn't appreciate the language that was being used.
I liked the enthusiasm and so forth, but the off-color stories that the Yale healers were using just seemed totally out of place with what I'd seen up to that point.
What was your evaluation of the quality of A&M students?
I thought they were good students.
Now, they were not what you would call Ivy League type or Ohio State type students.
I had done a master's at Ohio State, so I was surrounded by that.
But they were comparable to what maybe I saw at Kent State.
I would say they were comparable to that type of student.
In those early years, did they seem, could you categorize them by being urban or rural?
You said there were more women than men.
Yes.
Were they small town?
I think they were predominantly small town.
We were beginning to draw pretty heavily out of the Houston area at that time.
We were beginning to get some trickle from the Dallas area, which eventually grew.
As I said, everything seemed to double from year to year.
More and more of the urban types came in.
You saw
I saw a change in the wealth among the students.
My first year there, you seldom saw anything in the classification of a Cadillac or a Porsche or anything like that.
But that started to change rather rapidly.
Pretty soon, these kids were driving cars that I certainly couldn't afford to drive.
And that was a big change.
So the urban influx and the wealth
It seemed to change.
All right, let's go back now chronologically.
The College of Education is created in the late 60s.
69, opened in 69.
All right, and Dean Hubert becomes the dean.
And then what was your responsibility at that point?
Okay, now this was kind of unique, and this really shows the administrative skills of Frank W.R. Hubert.

Once Rudder and he knew that that college was going to be formed and going to open their doors in 1969, the fall, the previous academic years, Frank already identified who his department heads were going to be.
He was going to keep Carl Landis, who was head of the Department of Health and Physical Education.
That department was in the College of Liberal Arts.
It would come into the new College of Education.
the head of the Department of Industrial Education opted to stay in engineering.
So James Boone became the designated department head one year from then.
And that department would come out of engineering into the new College of Education.
The old Department of Education would become three departments.
Ed Administration and Les Richardson was tapped to head that up.
Educational Curriculum and Instruction was called Curriculum and Instruction to begin with.
And Frank asked me to head that up.
So this was my second year here, and he's already asked me to be head of a department.
And Art Roach was already here, and he would head up the new Department of Educational Psychology.
So the old Department of Education would disappear, and these three new departments would emerge, Ed Psych, Ed Administration, Curriculum, and Instruction.
But Frank Hubert had his five department heads identified.
We met with him.
It seemed like a weekly basis.
I'm sure it wasn't every week, but he was training us to become these three new department heads.
Carl Landis had the experience.
Jim Boone needed that kind of training, just like the three new department heads would have to have.
We went through budget.
We went through personnel selection.
We hired personnel.
We kept records, and none of this, you understand, was ever going to go anywhere because you couldn't process Form 500s to hire people under curriculum and instruction.
It was still the Department of Education.
Frank wore two hats.
He remained dean of the College of, was it Arts and Sciences or Liberal Arts by then?
I don't know.
I don't know.
Originally it was arts and sciences, and I don't know whether there was a split into liberal arts.
It may have split and become liberal arts by then, but he remained dean of that college and head of the Department of Education.
Paul was stepped down, and Frank became the new department.
So Frank was wearing two hats.
Half a day, he'd be up in the dean's office.
The other half day, he'd be down in the Department of Education working with all these new 2B department heads and trying to get the department organized for the changeover.
And I thought his foresight on that was just excellent.
Because boy, were those five department heads
ready when that door opened the following fall time.
Based on that preparation that he gave y'all, what do you think he thought were the keys to good leadership?
And I kind of had this impression as I got acquainted with and watched Dean Benson function over in engineering.
It seemed to me that Hubert and Benson had a similar kind of administrative style.
They delegated.
And Frank Hubert kept saying over and over to us, as prospect of new department heads all that previous year, you're going to assume responsibility for this.
You will make the decisions.
And he kept punching that home.
And as I watched Benson operate over in engineering, it seemed like he was operating that way too.
When he appointed somebody a department head, they ran the department.
And I think he and Frank Hubert thought philosophically, if you can't cut it, we'll get somebody else as the department head.
But as long as you're in the department, you're going to run it.
And even if I'm going to replace you, you're still going to run until I replace you, you know, type of thing.
And I like that because I came out, coming out of the administration, head administration training at Columbia University.
That was the philosophy there.
That as an administrator, you surrounded yourself with people who could assume responsibility and you turned them loose and gave them support.
And I always felt that way with Hubert, that I had the freedom to do and that he would support me.
Even if he didn't like it, I think he would still support me.
I think that was his philosophy.
How much was...
He a detailed person about dollars and cents.
Oh, tremendous.
He really understood the financial side of any organization.
And when we opened our doors in the fall of 69, we were pretty solid.
And I never felt threatened.
One of the things that I learned coming out of Columbia University's head administration training program was that two things will get you into big trouble very quickly.
And that's personnel problems and money.
And so I appreciated Hubert's philosophy, which followed that.
You better have good personnel
morally, ethically, and you better watch your money.
Even the money that he would be allocating to the departments, he made it very clear that it was going to be determined on how much student credit hour you could generate.
that he believed in the formula that Jack Kenny Williams had established when he was Commissioner of Education.
Jack Kenny Williams put that into operation, the student credit hour formula to finance universities and colleges, and Hubert simply carried it the next step, which was, okay,
In this college, you're going to function that way.
You have to generate student credit hours and allocate funding.
Pretty much now there were exceptions, of course.
He knew when somebody was getting a new program started, they would need a little extra
boost here and there.
When you became department head, do you remember who the faculty was, who were the faculty members in this new department?
Yes, well some of the key players by that time, I had hired Bob Schuetz, who would later become head of the department.
Five years later, I
for personal reasons, went up to Hubert and said, I've got a daughter.
We don't know what's wrong with her.
She's having problems.
I'm feeling stressed.
And I really, if you would be well, I'd really like to step out of this job.
And Frank's response was almost immediate.
He said, we're going to do whatever you want to do.
And I said, I want to do that.
And he said, well,
You know, I've got a new idea, and that is we've got some isolated higher education courses.
One over here in industrial, and one over here in ed psych.
There's one in your department and a couple in Ed's administration.
He said, I'd like to see those pulled together.
If you're going to step down, would you step in as kind of a coordinator of that effort?
It's not going to be demanding like the department head's job, but would you do that?
And I said, yes.
And he said, now, second question.
This shows how quick his mind works.
This was out of a clear blue sky.
I went up there and made this pronouncement to him that I really wanted to step down.
His next question was, who would be the department head of curriculum and instruction?
And I didn't hesitate to either.
I said, I know the faculty would support Bob Schutz.
So Bob had been one of the first hires that I made because I needed a really strong secondary education.
Harold was the guy I was trying to recall.
He was Bill Graves' counterpart.
And he had left or was leaving, I forget which.
So I needed someone now who could really head up secondary education.
The college had, or Dean Hubert had interviewed Bob Schutz for a research position, assistant dean for research, and he didn't have those qualifications.
But the credentials that I saw were overwhelming.
What a find this would be in secondary education.
He'd been sort of a coordinator of curriculum for secondary ed at one of the California schools.
He was co-author of a whole English textbook series for secondary schools.

So the offer coming out of the dean's office to Bob was not for assistant dean for research, but would you be interested in coming in and taking over the secondary education program in EDCI where Johnson's head of the department.
And Bob agreed to come in as my head of secondary education.
Two other key people that I hired was David David,
David dummy and David had that Bob's credentials.
at the elementary level.
He had been a very successful elementary person in the St. Louis County area.
And I was very impressed with his credentials, a graduate of the University of Missouri.
Bob Shutes was a graduate of Harvard.
And those were the kind of people I was looking for.
So I brought David in to head up elementary education.
And one thing that had bothered me immensely from really the first semester I was at Texas A&M was the mishandling of a whole area called history and philosophy of education.
They were having graduate students teach this who knew absolutely nothing
about the history of education or the philosophy of education, they would be assigned a senior level history and philosophy course to teach.
And they'd be given a textbook.
And they'd say, read this book and be prepared to start classes Monday.
And that just didn't settle with me.
Because if you knew anything about the history and philosophy
program at Columbia University.
Those were dynamic people.
They were nationally and internationally recognized people like Phil Phoenix, just a giant in the field.
So I wanted someone who had the right background.
And when I was up in Chicago,
at one of the national meetings, I put out the word that I wanted someone in history, philosophy, and that's when I found Jack Campbell.
Jack had a bachelor's degree in history.
He had been through the history and philosophical foundations program at Columbia University.
He had been head of a department.
in one of the New York University System schools.

He had gone out to a Pennsylvania school where he was a department head and I brought Jack in and Jack really did understand and know everything and was writing in that whole field so I felt a lot more comfortable
with people like Bob Schutz, David W. David, and Jack Campbell coming in with those kinds of credentials, I felt comfortable with what they were doing.
Did the doctoral program begin during those years?
Yes.
When the new college was formed, this was another thing that surprised all of us.

Whoever made the presentation to the coordinating board, it may have been Frank Hubert, it may have been one of the vice presidents, but whoever, it may have been some political things behind the scenes, but whoever did it, did it right because they approved right off the bat PhD programs in all five departments and EDD programs.
I think industrial education only had an EdD program, as I recall, and yet
coordinating board approved EDD and PhD programs for all five departments.
That immediately attracted students and our growth was immense.
I think that first year, by the end of the first year in curriculum and instruction, we had
Something like 300 master's degree students and pretty close to 90 doctoral students.
Do you remember when the first doctoral degree was completed in the department?
In the department?
No.
Were you department head?
Was it in that five years?
Yes, it was.
And I think it...
It could have been Jeannie Anderson.
I just have to go back and look.
But she was working on the PhD in Elm primarily.
although it was called curriculum and instruction, her area of concentration was really elementary education and reading.
And the reason I think she may have been the first is because Bill Graves was her chairman.
And it makes sense to me that it would have been someone that far along who would have come out of curriculum and instruction with Doreen.
I just don't recall.
Okay, looking back on those five years, what were the primary joys and frustrations of being a department head?
Well, the joy, of course, was seeing new faculty and new programs flourish.
That was just, you just felt very, very good about what was happening.
The frustration was the overwhelming number of students that were coming into the undergraduate, master's, and doctoral program.
with limited resources as far as providing the number of faculty members so you could reduce their loads.
People, by then, we may have been able to reduce their load by only one course.
We were probably down to everybody teaching four courses because we didn't have enough faculty.
to go around.
And y'all were not different from most of the other departments?
Oh no, no, that's true.
What about comparative salaries?
Were we reasonably competitive as far as you recall?
Not as I recall.
I don't think we really were competitive
with your major universities.
We could never compete with an Ohio State or a UCLA or a Southern Cal or Ohio State or Michigan.
We could not compete at that level.
But certainly anyone who couldn't, who wasn't at that level, where they could step
